The issue is clear. In `expression-builder.component.tsx`, the `useEffect` that resets state on `open`/`expression` change has this condition:

```ts
if (!isComplexRule) {
  setIsEditorEnabled(false);
  setIsPassThrough(false);
}
```

When you delete the expression in `form-expression-builder.component.tsx`, `helpers.setValue(null)` is called, which sets `field.value` to `null`. This causes `isComplexRule` to become `false` (via the `useEffect` watching `field.value`). However, the `ExpressionBuilder` dialog is not re-opened — `open` stays `false` — so the reset `useEffect` in `expression-builder.component.tsx` doesn't re-run to clear `isPassThrough`.

The real problem: `isPassThrough` is only reset when `open` changes or `expression` changes, but after deletion the dialog isn't opened again, so the stale `isPassThrough = true` persists into the next open.

The fix is simple — reset `isPassThrough` (and `isEditorEnabled`) unconditionally when `open` becomes `false`, regardless of `isComplexRule`:

diffs.oldStr:
  setState([...expression]);
  setFailed(false);
  return () => {
    if (!isComplexRule) {
      setIsEditorEnabled(false);
      setIsPassThrough(false);
    }
    setDdxErrors([]);
  };
}, [expression, open, isComplexRule]);

diffs.newStr:
  setState([...expression]);
  setFailed(false);
  if (!open) {
    setIsEditorEnabled(false);
    setIsPassThrough(false);
  }
  return () => {
    setDdxErrors([]);
  };
}, [expression, open, isComplexRule]);

